    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-03T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-03T17:00:00-05:00" n="735"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d735">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/33770: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-03T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >April 3, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1117. We fully approve of your action reported in your 2020, April 1, and we have
                    sent you in clear today the text of my statement to the press<note n="60"
                        xml:id="d735fn1">Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, April
                        8, 1944, p. 314.</note> expressing the deep regret of all of us over this
                    tragic incident as well as Ambassador Winant’s report of his and General
                    Spaatz’s call on the Swiss Chargé in London to express similar sentiments.
                    Assistant Secretary Long and the Director of the Office of European Affairs, Mr.
                    Dunn representing me, called on the Swiss Minister this afternoon to express in
                    person the regret of this Government over the incident and to inform the
                    Minister that an investigation was under way by the military authorities and as
                    soon as it was completed the findings would be made available to the
                    Minister.</p>
                <p>We hope the foregoing will be of some use to you in your conversations with Swiss
                    officials. If you have occasion to discuss the matter further with Mr.
                    Pilet-Golaz please express our deep appreciation for his orders that press and
                    radio announcements in Switzerland should be restrained and factual.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
